AGI - On May 30, 1944, exactly 80 years ago, the 35-year-old Eugenio Colorni died in the hospital due to the injuries reported following the assault of the Koch band near Piazza Bologna in Rome. Colorni was socialist, partisan, editor-in-chief of Avanti! clandestine and creator in 1941, during the confino of Ventotene with Altiero Spinelli and Ernesto Rossi, of the forefather manifesto 'For a free and united Europe', written while Hitler was still conquering the continent with his own armies. Saturday 8 and Sunday 9 <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-26/elections-ue-astensionism-festival-economics-trento-26532154/">will call for approximately 359 million European citizens </a> who will symbolically pay homage to the figure of Colorni. In 1941 Colorni, Spinelli and Rossi wrote valid words today: "The defeat of Germany would not automatically lead to the reorganization of Europe according to our ideal of civilization. The reactionary and conservative forces have skilled and accustomed men and paintings in command, who will fight eagerly to preserve their supremacy. Lovers of peace, freedom and the general well-being of the poorest classes will be proclaimed. The point on which they will try to leverage will be the restoration of the national state. If they reach this purpose they would win. The problem that must first be solved, and failing which any other progress is just appearance, is the definitive abolition of the division of Europe in sovereign national states."
&nbsp;
The new book by Antonio Tedesco 'Morire for Europe. Stories of struggles and freedoms > (Arcadia Edizioni) was presented at the headquarters of the Uil. Claim Claudio Martelli>: "Eugenio Colorni was the true inspiration of the Ventotene manifesto. He is socialist, philosopher, Milanese, influenced by the Jewish and Mazzinian culture. He writes the preface to the manifesto on the model of the United States of Europe. Its first point is the construction of a European army. Today it is too little to hypothesize only a European force of just 5 thousand men".
&nbsp;
Martelli, President of the Nenni Foundation, continues: "We made the single currency. We must now defend and make common foreign policy.> We need a European army. If you get attacked, you have to react aggressively. One-sided disarmament is a mess. You surrender to subditance. It is not possible to manifest in Gaza and at the same time ignore Ukraine." The former vicepremier criticizes Gramsci and his 'hate for indifferent': "Among an indifferent and a fascist, I prefer the indifferent. Not all faiths and passions are noble." German, in his book, speaks of five Italian Europeanists from the 1930s: Eugenio Colorni, Giorgio Braccialarghe, Libero Battistelli, Mario Pistocchi and Marcello Pasquale. Those and Battistelli sacrificed their lives for the ideal. Pistocchi will betray the cause by falling into the links of the West. Pasquale, captain of the Army, founded the subversive association 'Europe'.> Braccialarghe will become a leader of the Roman Resistance and the European Federalist Movement. "With this book - says Antonio Tedesco - I want to revive people of socialist, republican, european culture, fallen into the forgotten. Europe has guaranteed 75 years of peace and Erasmus is the most beautiful example of what these men have produced. The book wants to be a contribution to curb nationalisms, which are the origin of wars and imperialisms. Remembering the 80 years of Colorni's death is also a way of curbing the sovereign vents."
